INTRODUCTION
================================================================================

This document completes your financial system by addressing the remaining 2%:
DeFi (Decentralized Finance) tax treatment for UK residents.

DeFi encompasses:
• Lending protocols (Aave, Compound)
• Liquidity provision (Uniswap, Curve)
• Yield farming (various protocols)
• Staking (Ethereum 2.0, other PoS chains)
• Borrowing against crypto collateral
• Flash loans
• Governance token rewards

HMRC has issued specific guidance on DeFi taxation (Cryptoassets Manual).
This guide translates that guidance into actionable steps.

================================================================================
PART 1: DEFI ACTIVITIES AND THEIR TAX TREATMENT
================================================================================

1.1 CRYPTO LENDING (EARN INTEREST)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Activity: You deposit crypto to a lending protocol (Aave, Compound) and earn
interest paid in the same or different crypto.

Tax Treatment: INCOME TAX (not Capital Gains Tax)

Why: You are providing a service (lending) and receiving income (interest).
This is analogous to bank interest or savings income.

Calculation:
• Taxable amount = GBP value of interest at receipt
• Tax rate: Income Tax bands (20% basic, 40% higher, 45% additional)
• Trading Allowance: £1,000/year may apply if total trading income under £1,000
• If over £1,000: Full Income Tax applies

Example:
• You deposit 1 ETH to Aave
• Earn 0.05 ETH interest over 6 months
• When received, 0.05 ETH = £100
• Taxable income: £100
• Tax due (basic rate): £20
• If under £1,000 total trading income: £0 (Trading Allowance)

Record Keeping:
• Date of deposit
• Amount deposited
• Date interest received
• Amount of interest (in crypto and GBP)
• GBP exchange rate at receipt
• Protocol used (Aave, Compound, etc.)

1.2 LIQUIDITY PROVISION (DEX LP TOKENS)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Activity: You deposit crypto pairs to a DEX (Uniswap, Curve) and receive:
• LP tokens representing your share
• Trading fees as additional crypto
• Sometimes governance tokens as rewards

Tax Treatment: MIXED - depends on specific circumstances

A) TRADING FEES:
• Treated as income when received
• GBP value at receipt = taxable income
• Income Tax applies (or Trading Allowance if applicable)

B) LP TOKEN VALUE CHANGES:
• LP tokens represent your underlying asset share
• When you withdraw, compare value to deposit
• GAIN: Capital Gains Tax
• LOSS: Capital loss (offset against gains)

Example:
• Deposit: 1 ETH (£1,500) + 3000 USDC (£1,500) = £3,000
• Receive LP tokens representing pool share
• Earn fees: 0.1 ETH (£150) over 3 months
• Fee income: £150 (Income Tax)
• After 6 months, withdraw
• Receive: 0.9 ETH (£1,350) + 3100 USDC (£1,550) = £2,900
• Capital loss: £3,000 - £2,900 = £100 (CGT loss)

C) GOVERNANCE TOKEN REWARDS:
• Treated as income at receipt
• GBP value when received = taxable
• Income Tax applies
• If token appreciates: subsequent sale subject to CGT

1.3 YIELD FARMING (MULTIPLE PROTOCOLS)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Activity: Complex strategies moving funds between protocols to maximize yield.
May involve:
• Depositing to Protocol A
• Receiving Token B
• Staking Token B in Protocol C
• Receiving Token D
• Selling Token D for original asset

Tax Treatment: HIGHLY LIKELY TO BE TRADING (Income Tax)

Why: HMRC "Badges of Trade" test likely applies:
• Frequency of transactions (high in yield farming)
• Sophistication (complex multi-step strategies)
• Intent (profit motive clear)
• Duration (funds not held long-term)
• Risk level (actively managed)

Calculation:
• Each step may be taxable event
• Income Tax on rewards at receipt
• CGT on disposals
• NET profit subject to Income Tax (if trading)
• Trading Allowance: £1,000 if applicable

Example - Complex Yield Farm:
Day 1: Deposit 1 ETH (£1,500) to Protocol A
Day 2: Receive 1000 TOKEN-A (worth £100) - INCOME £100
Day 3: Stake TOKEN-A in Protocol B
Day 4: Receive 50 TOKEN-B (worth £60) - INCOME £60
Day 5: Sell TOKEN-B for 0.04 ETH (£60)
Day 10: Claim rewards from Protocol A: 0.02 ETH (£30) - INCOME £30
Day 30: Withdraw from Protocol B, receive 800 TOKEN-A (worth £80)
Day 31: Sell 800 TOKEN-A for 0.05 ETH (£75)

Tax Calculation:
• Income from rewards: £100 + £60 + £30 = £190
• Disposals for CGT: Multiple events
• If deemed trading: Full £190 + gains/losses = Income Tax
• If deemed investing: Income £190 + CGT on disposals

1.4 BORROWING AGAINST CRYPTO COLLATERAL
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Activity: You deposit crypto as collateral and borrow stablecoins/other crypto.

Tax Treatment: NOT TAXABLE (loan)

Why: Borrowing is not a taxable event. You receive loan, not income.

However:
• LIQUIDATION: If collateral liquidated = DISPOSAL (CGT event)
• INTEREST PAID: Not deductible for personal borrowing
• INTEREST EARNED on borrowed funds: Taxable income

Example:
• Deposit 2 ETH (£3,000) as collateral
• Borrow 1000 USDC (£1,000)
• No tax on borrowing
• If ETH drops, collateral liquidated at 1.8 ETH (£2,700)
• Disposal: 0.2 ETH = £300 (CGT calculation needed)

1.5 FLASH LOANS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Activity: Borrow large amounts instantly, use in single transaction, repay.
Profit from arbitrage or self-liquidation.

Tax Treatment: TRADING (Income Tax) almost certainly

Why:
• Sophisticated financial instrument
• Short-term (seconds)
• Profit motive
• Technical execution
• Commercial nature

Calculation:
• Profit from flash loan = Income
• Income Tax applies (20%/40%/45%)
• Trading Allowance: £1,000 if applicable
• No CGT (not capital asset disposal)

Example:
• Flash borrow 1000 ETH
• Execute arbitrage, profit 5 ETH (£7,500)
• Repay 1000 ETH + 0.1 ETH fee
• Net profit: 4.9 ETH (£7,350)
• Taxable income: £7,350
• Tax due (basic): £1,470

1.6 STAKING (PROOF OF STAKE)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Activity: Lock crypto to validate network, earn staking rewards.

Tax Treatment: INCOME TAX (new HMRC guidance)

Previous uncertainty resolved:
• Staking rewards = Income Tax at receipt
• GBP value when received
• Trading Allowance: £1,000 if applicable
• Validator vs delegator: Same treatment

Special Cases:
• ETH 2.0 staking (locked until Shanghai upgrade): Tax on rewards when accessible
• Some protocols: Rewards auto-compound (tax when received/claimable)

Example:
• Stake 32 ETH as validator
• Earn 0.5 ETH rewards over month
• When claimable: £750 value
• Taxable income: £750
• Tax due (basic): £150

1.7 GOVERNANCE TOKENS AND AIRDROP
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Activity: Receive tokens for participating in protocol governance or airdrops.

Tax Treatment: INCOME TAX at receipt

Calculation:
• GBP value when received/claimable
• Income Tax applies
• If later sold: CGT on any gain since receipt
• If value drops to zero: Capital loss

Exception - Retroactive Airdrops:
• If airdrop for past activity (not future services)
• May be treated as CGT event
• Consult accountant for specific cases

================================================================================
PART 2: HMRC GUIDANCE AND COMPLIANCE
================================================================================

2.1 CRYPTOASSETS MANUAL (CMA) RELEVANT SECTIONS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

HMRC's official guidance:
• CMA1130: Lending, staking, DeFi
• CMA1140: Income from lending/staking
• CMA1150: Disposals in DeFi
• CMA1100: General principles

Key HMRC Position:
"Returns from lending or staking cryptoassets will generally be subject to
Income Tax, not Capital Gains Tax."

2.2 WHEN IS DEFI TRADING VS INVESTING?
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

HMRC uses "Badges of Trade" to determine if trading:

Badge                          DeFi Trader       DeFi Investor
-----------------------------  ----------------  -------------------
Frequency of transactions      High (daily+)     Low (monthly+)
Sophistication                 High              Low-Medium
Intent                         Profit motive     Long-term hold
Duration                       Short-term        Long-term
Risk management                Active            Passive
Organization                   Business-like     Personal

DeFi Tax Outcome:
• TRADER: Income Tax on profits, expenses deductible
• INVESTOR: Income Tax on rewards, CGT on gains/losses

Most DeFi activity = TRADING classification due to complexity

2.3 SECTION 104 POOLING IN DEFI
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Cryptoassets held for CGT purposes use Section 104 pooling:
• All same-type cryptoassets pooled together
• Average cost basis calculated
• DeFi deposits: Still in pool (not disposal)
• DeFi withdrawals: Add back to pool

Exceptions - Disposals:
• Lending crypto to third party (not protocol) = disposal
• Collateral liquidated = disposal
• Token swaps within DeFi = disposal

2.4 SAME DAY AND BED AND BREAKFAST RULES
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

If you sell and rebuy same crypto within 30 days:
• Same Day Rule: Match acquisitions/disposals same day
• 30-Day Rule (Bed and Breakfast): Match acquisitions within 30 days
• Section 104: Remaining pool

DeFi Impact:
• Frequent DeFi transactions may trigger these rules
• Complex tracking required
• Software like Koinly handles this automatically

================================================================================
PART 3: RECORD KEEPING FOR DEFI
================================================================================

3.1 REQUIRED RECORDS (HMRC REQUIREMENTS)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

For each DeFi transaction, record:
• Date and time
• Type of activity (lend, borrow, stake, farm, etc.)
• Protocol/platform used
• Cryptoasset type and amount
• GBP value at transaction
• Any fees paid
• Rewards/income received
• Wallet addresses involved
• Transaction hashes

3.2 TRACKING METHODS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

A) MANUAL SPREADSHEET (Not Recommended for Active DeFi)
Columns needed:
- Date | Activity | Protocol | Asset In | Amount In | GBP In | Asset Out | Amount Out | GBP Out | Fees (GBP) | Net (GBP) | Notes

B) AUTOMATED SOFTWARE (Recommended)
Koinly (Crypto Tax Calculator):
• Connects to wallets via API or CSV
• Tracks DeFi transactions automatically
• Identifies taxable events
• Calculates Income Tax and CGT
• Generates HMRC-compliant reports

Supported Protocols (partial list):
• Aave, Compound (lending)
• Uniswap, Curve, Balancer (DEX/LP)
• Convex, Yearn (yield farming)
• Lido, Rocket Pool (staking)
• Various bridges and cross-chain protocols

3.3 WALLET CONNECTION METHODS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

For tracking DeFi, connect:
• Ethereum mainnet wallet (MetaMask, etc.)
• Layer 2 wallets (Arbitrum, Optimism, Polygon)
• Other chains if applicable (BSC, Avalanche, etc.)

Connection types:
• API read-only: Preferred (secure)
• Public address: Manual CSV import
• Private key: NEVER for tax software

3.4 DEFI SPECIFIC CHALLENGES
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Challenge 1: Impermanent Loss
• LP tokens may be worth less than deposited assets
• Tax software tracks this as capital loss
• Ensure correct GBP conversion at deposit/withdrawal

Challenge 2: Reward Tokens
• May have no market value at receipt
• Use fair market value or £0 if truly no value
• Document methodology

Challenge 3: Failed Transactions
• Gas fees on failed transactions
• Not deductible as no disposal occurred
• Keep records anyway

Challenge 4: Cross-Chain Bridges
• Moving assets between chains
• Not taxable if same ownership
• Bridge fees may be deductible (if trading)

Challenge 5: Governance Participation
• Voting may have tax implications
• Generally not taxable unless paid to vote
• Airdrops for voting = taxable income

================================================================================
PART 4: PRACTICAL EXAMPLES AND CALCULATIONS
================================================================================

4.1 EXAMPLE 1: SIMPLE AAVE LENDING
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Scenario:
• March 1: Deposit 1 ETH (£1,800) to Aave
• March 31: aETH balance shows 1.02 ETH (£1,920 value)
• June 30: Withdraw 1.05 ETH (£2,100)

Tax Treatment:
• March 1: No tax (deposit)
• March 31: Interest accrued but not received = NO TAX
• June 30: Withdrawal triggers recognition
  - Interest received: 0.05 ETH = £100 (value at withdrawal)
  - Taxable income: £100
  - Tax due (basic): £20

Note: If withdrawn in stages, each withdrawal triggers tax on proportion

4.2 EXAMPLE 2: UNISWAP LIQUIDITY PROVISION
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Scenario:
• Deposit 0.5 ETH (£900) + 1800 USDC (£900)
• Receive LP tokens
• Over 3 months earn fees: 0.02 ETH (£40) + 80 USDC (£40)
• Also receive 100 UNI tokens (airdrop worth £50)
• Withdraw after 3 months: 0.48 ETH (£840) + 1850 USDC (£925)

Tax Calculation:
1. Trading Fees Income: £40 + £40 = £80 (Income Tax)
2. Airdrop Income: £50 (Income Tax)
3. Capital Calculation:
   - Deposit: £1,800
   - Withdrawal value: £840 + £925 = £1,765
   - Capital loss: £35
   - Claim against other gains

Total Income: £130
Tax (basic rate): £26 (or £0 if under £1,000 Trading Allowance)

4.3 EXAMPLE 3: COMPLEX YIELD FARMING
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Scenario:
• Week 1: Deposit ETH to Protocol A, receive TOKEN-A
• Week 2: Stake TOKEN-A, receive TOKEN-B rewards
• Week 3: Sell half TOKEN-B for ETH
• Week 4: Compound rewards back into Protocol A
• Month 2: Exit position, various tokens received

HMRC Likely Classification: TRADING

Tax Treatment:
• Each reward receipt = Income Tax event
• Each disposal/swap = CGT event
• Net profit = Income Tax (trading classification)
• Trading Allowance: £1,000 if applicable

Recommendation: Treat as trading from outset. Keep meticulous records.

4.4 EXAMPLE 4: ETH 2.0 STAKING
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Scenario:
• December 2020: Stake 32 ETH (£12,000)
• Cannot withdraw until Shanghai upgrade
• Rewards accrue but locked

Tax Treatment (Pre-Shanghai):
• Rewards earned but not accessible = NO TAX
• Similar to accrued interest not yet paid

Tax Treatment (Post-Shanghai):
• When rewards become withdrawable = TAX TRIGGER
• GBP value at first accessibility = Income Tax
• Subsequent rewards as received

Example:
• Shanghai upgrade: April 2026
• Rewards accessible: 4 ETH (£8,000)
• Taxable income: £8,000 (in Year 2026/27)
• Tax due (basic): £1,600

